The **SWE Diagramming** project adopts a research and exploratory orientation, focusing on experimental techniques for generating, mapping or reasoning about software diagrams directly from source code and related artifacts. The core idea is to investigate how automated visualization and representation can improve comprehension, debugging and design validation for complex systems.

## Research

Potentially useful resources:

- GitHub Repos: [Awesome Diagramming](https://github.com/shubhamgrg04/awesome-diagramming)  
- [Github RESTFUL API](https://docs.github.com/en/rest?apiVersion=2022-11-28)

Example existing software:

- [GitDiagram](https://gitdiagram.com)  
- [MermaidJS](https://mermaid.js.org/)  
- [DeepWiki](https://deepwiki.com/)

## Users and User Stories

Potential end-users: 

- A **researcher** focuses on studying how the diagramming tools support software design validation and mapping of artifacts.  
- A **software engineer** who regularly writes and refactors code and explores architecture.  
  - **QA and Test engineers** who want a better understanding of the repo to provide better test coverage  
  - A **newly onboarded engineer** who needs to learn and understand the new codebases  
  - A **software team leader** (i.e., senior or staff dev) who wants to get a big picture of the whole project and improve management  
- A person who is **new to software development** and engineering (i.e., first-year CS, non-technical people taking an intro course)  
- A **product manager** or a more business-oriented cross-functional team member who isn’t necessarily that involved in the development  
  - A project manager trying to *document* an open-source project

Stories:  
**Person new to software development:**

- Just pulled a remote repository, and want to analyze locally, or a specific part subfolder of it (input: local folder path, output: diagram showing the internal logic between modules in the repo \+ general description of the diagram)  
- Saw a interesting project on github, and readme is not that informative, want to use its repo url to get more insight (public or private) (input: url  
- Other types of cloud codebase e.g. google drive/cseweb.ucsd.edu/  (input: url)

**Newly onboarded engineer:**

- As a newly onboard engineer, I want to quickly identify core logics of the project (both frontend and backend), and potentially use prompt to identify where my development task is located.  
- As a newly onboarded engineer, I want to see a top level overview of the codebase architecture so I can instantly get a visual summary of where each component is

**Researcher:**

- As a researcher, I want to automatically generate mapping between code components and architecture diagrams so that I can see how structural complexity evolves over time.  
- As a researcher, I want to experiment how different visualizations layout affect developers’ understanding of the codebase so that I can identify the most cognitively effective visual encodings.  
- As a researcher, I want to collect structural feedback after user interaction so that I can refine the generation algorithm based on user feedback.

**Product Manager:**

- As a Product Manager, I want to visualize the architecture of a feature directly from the source code so that I can understand how different modules interact without relying solely on engineers’ explanations.  
- As a Product Designer, I want to see how the backend components connect to the UI or API endpoints so that I can ensure the user experience aligns with system capabilities and constraints.  
- As a Product Manager, I want automatically generated diagrams that I can share in sprint reviews and planning meetings so that technical discussions are grounded in clear visual references.

**Software Team Lead:**

- As a software team lead, I want to automatically visualize my team codebase’s system architecture so that I can confirm the implementation matches the original design.  
- As a software team lead, I want to track system architecture diagrams that evolve across sprints so that I can detect emergent technical debt or architectural drift early.

**QA and Test engineers** :

- As a QA and Test engineer, I want to be able to see a breakdown of each component to get a better understanding of the component to make better tests.   
- As a QA engineer, I want the tool to have the ability to re-focus on the QA parts (e.g. test files’ relation with modules & brief test coverage) in addition to general analysis. Probably by prompt or asking for my role in advance.  
- As a QA and Test engineer, I want to be able to visualize the branch structure and commits of a repo so I can understand the development flow and identify potential risks such as unmerged branches, or conflicting changes.

## Requirements

- Webapp(single page) first, if successful then try to migrate to desktop app (or browser extension)?  
- Output expected: mermaid diagram (text generalization? Prompt window for re-focusing?)  
- Be able to handle large GitHub repos as input (500+ files)  
- Version control with GitHub  
- Be able to cache previously generated graphs for codebase for faster retrieval of the same codebase for subsequent requests.  
- Be able to parse through Git History including commits, merges, branches, and tags  
- Accept GitHub repository URL (public repos) as input  
- Structure of the diagram should be consistent with dependencies  
- History should be cached locally

## Features

- Construct in-depth documentation based on the diagram (README, ADRs, etc.)  
- List all components and latest commit author/date  
- Provide a brief summary of what each component contains (can do this with LLM, or maybe just pull the comment at the top because general good coding practices would have each file labeled at the top anyway?)  
- Generate an architecture diagram for the repo  
  - for the selected commit/branch in the codebase  
    - Dropdown to select branches from repo to display  
    - in a split view (in addition to existing diagrams AKA multiple diagrams at once)  
  - Easy navtools to move to parts of the codebase in the diagram quickly  
- Annotate diagrams with notes and highlights  
- ~~Filter committed based on different authors, branches, and tags~~  
- Export diagram as PNG/SVG or embedded links  
  - Share to tools like slack, jira, github  
- Import via GitHub Link  
- Feature to take a zip file as an alternate input (accessibility)  
- Display Repository metrics  
  - file counts  
  - primary language (repo makeup)  
  - folder depth  
- If we are using MermaidJS API to make the architecture \- Give in-built option to edit mermaidJS code  
  - Export/copy mermaidJS code  
- Cache previously analyzed repo and show them on the page, like what DeepWiki did  
  - Example diagrams  
  - Show change history of the diagram (like diff check)  
- Private access tokens option for private repos  
- Identify user type and specialize the analysis based on user type (e.g. QA \-\> focus on testing, backend \-\> focus on database & api, frontend \-\> focus on frontend components, new comer \-\> more explanation less tech detail)
